417–Deceased","1419–Male":"1419–Deceased","1369–Male":"1369–Deceased","1374–Female":"1374–Deceased","1369":"1369","Abt 1419":"about 1419","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","1393":"1393","1419":"1419","Abt 1417":"about 1417","Abt 1416":"about 1416","1417":"1417","Of, Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, England","Wisbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"Wisbech, Cambridgeshire, England","Of, Wysbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Fleet, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Fleet, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fleet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Middle English <i>flete</i> ‘estuary, watercourse’ (Old English <i>flēot</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived beside an estuary or watercourse, or toponymic, from a place so named, such as Fleet in Lincolnshire, Dorset, Kent, Middlesex, Hampshire or Holt Fleet, Worcestershire.","nickname for a swift runner, from Middle English <i>flete</i> ‘swift, rapid’."],"variants":[{"name":"Flett","meanings":["Scottish: probably a habitational name from a place in the parish of Delting, Shetland, named with an Old Norse term denoting a strip of arable land or pasture. On the other hand it may be from the Old Norse byname <i>Fljótr</i> ‘swift, speedy’. Compare   Fleet   2. The surname is now most common in Banffshire and Orkney."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":60,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Fleet was born in 1395, in Wisbech, Cambridgeshire, England, her father, Sir Lawrence Fleet Knight, was 26 and her mother, Lady Lawrence Fleet, was 21. She married Richard Bartholomew Everard III about 1416, in Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"1395–":"1395–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1393–1423":"1393–1423","1417–Male":"1417–Surnud","1419–Male":"1419–Surnud","1369–Male":"1369–Surnud","1374–Female":"1374–Surnud","1369":"1369","Abt 1419":"umbes 1419","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","1393":"1393","1419":"1419","Abt 1417":"umbes 1417","Abt 1416":"umbes 1416","1417":"1417","Of, Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, England","Wisbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"Wisbech, Cambridgeshire, England","Of, Wysbech, Cambridgeshi